"""
MKT Original Commentary — Numbers 32–33
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-numbers-32-33.py

Key decisions:
- Ch 32: The Transjordan tribes' request — the theological parallel to Lot's choice (Gen 13) and
  the spy-generation; "your sin will find you out" (v23); the conditional covenant sealed with
  Eleazar and Joshua rather than Moses alone signals succession awareness
- Ch 33: The wilderness itinerary — Moses wrote it "at YHWH's command" (v2), making it a
  divinely authorized travel-memoir not just geography; 42 stations = 40 years of wandering;
  the chapter ends with conquest instructions (v50-56) whose conditional warning (v55-56)
  foreshadows the Judges narrative
- YHWH throughout per project convention
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "32": {
    "1": "<p>The Transjordan settlement request opens the final section of Numbers. The tribes of Reuben and Gad observe that the already-conquered territories east of the Jordan — Jazer and Gilead — are prime grazing land (<em>meqom miqneh</em>, livestock country). The fact that they have 'very large herds' (<em>miqneh rav me'od</em>) motivates the request: pastoral wealth drives this claim. The echo of Lot's choice in Gen 13:10-11 is unmistakable — Lot 'lifted his eyes' and saw the well-watered Jordan valley; the Reubenites and Gadites 'saw the land of Jazer and Gilead.' Both prioritize visible abundance over covenant commitments.</p>",
    "2": "<p>They bring the request to the full leadership triad: Moses, Eleazar the priest, and the community leaders (<em>nesiei ha'edah</em>). The formal submission to the three-tiered authority structure reflects the gravity of the request — this is not a private negotiation but a public covenant claim. Eleazar's inclusion alongside Moses is significant: as Aaron's successor, his presence represents the priestly establishment that will survive the wilderness generation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The cities they enumerate — Ataroth, Dibon, Jazer, Nimrah, Heshbon, Elealeh, Sebam, Nebo, Beon — are all in the Transjordan, east of the Dead Sea and northern Jordan. These are territories already conquered from Sihon king of the Amorites and Og king of Bashan (Num 21:21-35). The petitioners are not asking for unconquered territory; they are asking for land that YHWH has already given into Israel's hand — land that already flows with the provision of good pasture.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>ha'aretz asher hikah YHWH lifney adat Yisrael eretz miqneh hi</strong>: 'The land which YHWH struck down before the congregation of Israel is livestock country.' The petitioners ground their request in YHWH's own action: the land is available because YHWH gave it. This is the strongest possible argument — they are not asking for what has not been conquered but for what YHWH has already given. The theological problem is not the land's availability but what the request will signal to the rest of the congregation about commitment to the Canaan campaign.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>al ta'avireinu et haYarden</strong>: 'Do not make us cross the Jordan.' The phrase is the crux of Moses's alarm: the Gadites and Reubenites are asking to opt out of the Jordan-crossing, which is the central act of inheriting the promised land. The Jordan crossing is the covenant's geographic fulfillment; to not cross is to position oneself outside the central promise. Moses immediately connects this to the spies' failure — the language of 'not crossing' activates the Num 13-14 memory.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>ha'acheichem yavo'u lamilchamah ve'atem teshvu po</strong>: 'Are your brothers to go off to war while you settle here?' Moses's first response is a question that exposes the moral problem: their comfort while the rest of Israel fights creates the same division of sacrifice that tribal solidarity is meant to prevent. The question mirrors the challenge to shirkers in any shared military obligation — but here the shared obligation is the covenant-gift of the promised land itself.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>lamah teniche'un et lev beney Yisrael</strong>: 'Why would you discourage (<em>niche'</em>) the Israelites?' The verb <em>nache'</em> (Hiphil of <em>nua'</em> = to make waver/discourage) is the same word used in 32:9 for what the spies did to the congregation. Moses hears the Gadite-Reubenite request as a structural repetition of the spy-disaster: just as the spies' negative report turned the congregation's heart away from entering the land, so the visible decision of two large tribes to settle outside Canaan will discourage the remaining tribes from pressing into the promise.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Moses appeals to historical precedent: 'Your ancestors did the same thing when I sent them from Kadesh-barnea.' The spy narrative (Num 13-14) is the primary theological frame Moses applies to the current situation. The parallel is exact: the spies were sent to scout a land YHWH had promised to give; the spies returned and discouraged the congregation; YHWH's anger blazed; forty years of wandering followed. Moses sees the same pattern repeating with the next generation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Valley of Eshcol was where the spies cut the enormous cluster of grapes — the tangible proof that Canaan was the promised land. The spies 'surveyed the land' and 'turned the heart of the Israelites from going into the land YHWH had given them.' The phrase <em>vayenifu et lev beney Yisrael</em> (they caused the heart of Israel to waver) uses the same <em>nache'</em> vocabulary as v7: the ancestors' sin was precisely the sin Moses fears the Gadites and Reubenites are about to repeat.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>vayichar af YHWH bayom hahu vayishava</strong>: 'The LORD's anger blazed that day and he swore.' YHWH's oath-response to the spy generation's failure (Num 14:20-35) was the most severe judgment in the wilderness narrative: the entire generation over 20 must die in the desert before the next generation enters. Moses invokes that oath precisely here to make the Gadites and Reubenites aware of the category of sin they are approaching.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The oath's content: 'Not one of the men who came out of Egypt, twenty years old or above, will ever see the land I swore to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.' The Abrahamic covenant — the three patriarchal names — frames the promised land as the goal of a covenant stretching back four generations. The land is not a real-estate transaction but a covenant inheritance. Failing to pursue it is covenant disloyalty of the highest order.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>ki male'u acharey YHWH</strong>: 'they followed YHWH fully.' The phrase applied to Caleb and Joshua — <em>mille'u acharey YHWH</em> (lit. they filled/were full behind YHWH) — is the theological standard against which the spy generation failed and against which Moses will measure the Gadites and Reubenites. 'Full-following' is the antithesis of the wavering heart. The conditional promise Moses offers in v20-22 is built on this same standard: 'if you truly arm yourselves before YHWH' — the Gadites and Reubenites can demonstrate full-following by keeping their commitment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The forty-year wandering is presented explicitly as divine punishment: 'The LORD's anger burned against Israel and he made them wander in the wilderness forty years, until the whole generation who had done evil in YHWH's sight had finished.' The word <em>tamam</em> (to come to an end/finish) describes the death of the guilty generation — the forty years are not arbitrary but the time required for the disobedient generation to die out. Every year of wandering represents the covenant's demand that covenant-refusal has consequences.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>vataqumun tachteyhem torevet anashim chata'im</strong>: 'And here you are — a brood of sinful men — risen in your fathers' footsteps.' The phrase <em>tarbut anashim chata'im</em> (increase/brood of sinful men) is Moses's harshest language in the chapter — he calls the petitioners the direct offspring of the guilty generation, implying that the same sinful pattern is being replicated generationally. 'To stoke the LORD's fierce anger against Israel' — Moses sees the request as triggering the same divine wrath that burned against the fathers.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>ki tishuvu me'acharav</strong>: 'If you turn away from following him.' The conditional threat: if Reuben and Gad stay behind, their defection will trigger a new wilderness abandonment for all Israel. 'He will again abandon them in the wilderness' — the word <em>od</em> (again) invokes the first abandonment as the pattern to be repeated. Moses's response is not merely personal disappointment but prophetic warning: the tribes' choice affects the entire covenant community. Individual covenant decisions ripple out to the whole people.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The tribes respond with a concrete counter-proposal: 'We will build sheepfolds here for our livestock and towns for our little ones.' They do not dispute Moses's theological framework — they accept the obligation to support the Canaan campaign; they propose a way to do so while also securing their families and flocks. The proposal is practical and essentially fair: leave dependents and property settled in the east; go west as armed vanguard. The construction of cities for children (<em>taph</em>) and sheepfolds (<em>gidroth tzon</em>) is the domestic security that makes the military commitment possible.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>va'anachnu ne'chalets cheushim lifney beney Yisrael</strong>: 'We ourselves will arm for battle and march ahead of the Israelites.' <em>Ne'chaletz</em> (armed/girded for battle) is the military readiness term — not merely alongside Israel but ahead of them, as the vanguard. The proposal is actually more than Moses asked for: they offer not to parallel Israel's advance but to lead it. The phrase 'until every tribe is settled in its place' defines the duration of their military obligation: until all of Israel has received its inheritance, not merely until their own territory is secure.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>lo nashuv el batteinu ad hithnachel beney Yisrael</strong>: 'We will not return home until every Israelite has received his inheritance.' The completeness of the commitment is explicit — not 'until we've done our share' but until <em>every Israelite</em> is settled. The word <em>ish nachalatho</em> (each man his inheritance) uses the covenant-inheritance vocabulary that frames the entire land distribution. The Gadites and Reubenites are not exempting themselves from covenant solidarity but expressing it in a concrete form.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The tribes clarify why they are not taking an inheritance in Canaan proper: 'because our inheritance has come to us on this side of the Jordan, on the east.' The Transjordan territory is their portion — they accept the covenant-promise in its eastern form. This verse resolves the ambiguity of their request: they are not refusing the covenant-inheritance but locating it in the already-conquered Transjordan rather than in the not-yet-conquered Cisjordan. From their perspective, YHWH has already given them their inheritance.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>im ta'asun zo't</strong>: 'If you will truly do this.' Moses's acceptance is conditional, marked by four <em>im</em> (if) clauses that build from the initial condition (arm for battle) through the process (cross the Jordan) to the endpoint (land subdued before YHWH). The double 'before YHWH' (<em>lifney YHWH</em>) in v20-21 frames the military campaign as a divine-presence operation: they cross not merely with Israel but 'before YHWH,' in the march of the covenant presence.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>ve'avar lachem kol chaluts et haYarden lifney YHWH</strong>: The crossing is 'before YHWH' — the ark of the covenant leads the march and the armed troops cross in relation to the covenant presence. The military and the liturgical are inseparable in Israel's conquest theology: the land is taken in YHWH's presence, under YHWH's authorization, and the armed force is technically the extension of YHWH's own army. To march 'before YHWH' is not a metaphor but a reference to the ark-procession of conquest.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>veniqitem meYHWH umiyisrael</strong>: 'You will be free of obligation to YHWH and to Israel.' The completion of the military commitment releases them from both divine and communal obligation — the covenant duty has two dimensions: YHWH's claim (the land-conquest is divinely commanded) and Israel's claim (tribal solidarity requires shared sacrifice). Fulfilling both dimensions through armed vanguard service settles both accounts. The language anticipates the formal release Joshua gives the Transjordan tribes in Josh 22:1-6.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>uve'u chatatchem etckem</strong>: 'Know that your sin will find you out.' This single phrase has become a proverbial statement of moral accountability in English ('your sin will find you out'). The original context is Moses's conditional warning: if they break their military commitment, their sin (<em>chet</em>) will 'find' them — the verb <em>matza</em> (find) suggests the inevitability of consequence, as if sin were an active pursuer. The warning is not a threat but a statement of moral physics: covenant-breaking carries its own consequences regardless of whether anyone else enforces them.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Moses accepts the proposal: 'Go ahead — build towns for your children and pens for your flocks, and carry out what you have promised.' The phrase <em>hayotzeh mipikem ta'asu</em> (what has gone out of your mouth, do) invokes the principle of oath-fulfillment: spoken promises are binding. The permission to build domestically (cities for children, pens for flocks) is the practical implementation of the deal — Moses gives them what they asked for on the condition that they fulfill what they promised.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The formal acceptance: 'Your servants will do as my lord commands.' The language is the standard formula of covenant-acceptance in the ancient world — the subordinate party acknowledges the superior's authority and affirms compliance. 'Your servants' (<em>avadeicha</em>) and 'my lord' (<em>adoni</em>) establish the hierarchical relationship while marking the commitment as mutual and binding.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The specific arrangement: children (<em>taph</em>), wives (<em>nashim</em>), flocks (<em>tzon</em>), and all livestock stay in the cities of Gilead. The specificity of the list — every category of dependent — emphasizes that the men will leave behind everything that requires protection, trusting YHWH and Moses's arrangements to preserve their families while they fight. The risk of the commitment is real: their families are vulnerable; they are betting on YHWH's faithfulness to their covenant-keeping.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>va'avadeicha ya'avru kol chaluts tzava lifney YHWH lamilchamah</strong>: 'All your servants, every armed man, will cross before YHWH to battle.' The repetition of 'before YHWH' (v21, v27) frames the military crossing as the central theological act. The armed service they offer is not secular soldiering but covenant warfare — marching in the manifest presence of YHWH as he fights for his people. This is the theological understanding of holy war (<em>herem</em>) warfare in the conquest tradition.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Moses records the agreement with Eleazar, Joshua, and the tribal heads — the full institutional leadership. The presence of Joshua in the covenant witnesses is significant: the Transjordan promise will be fulfilled under Joshua's command, not Moses's. Moses is recording a commitment that will be enforced by his successor. The formal witness list (priest + military leader + tribal heads) constitutes the maximum legal accountability in Israel's system.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The legal conditions stated formally: if the Gadites and Reubenites cross armed before YHWH and the land is subdued, then give them the Transjordan. The if-then structure mirrors the conditional covenant framework throughout Numbers: YHWH's promises are not unconditional grants but covenant commitments that require faithful response. The Transjordan inheritance is secured by their faithful military service, not by their having already claimed the land.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The sanction: if they do not fulfill the military commitment, 'they will receive their share in Canaan.' The sanction is not punishment per se but loss of the specific request — they would be forced to receive a Cisjordan inheritance like everyone else, rather than the Transjordan territory they desired. The sanction preserves their covenant status (they still get inheritance) while removing the specific accommodation they requested. This is proportionate consequence within the covenant framework.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>ka'asher diber YHWH el avadeicha ken na'aseh</strong>: 'What the LORD has said, we will do.' The final acceptance is specifically attributed to YHWH's word through Moses — they are not merely agreeing with Moses's personal judgment but with YHWH's directive. The oath-formula includes 'we' — it is a communal commitment, binding on the entire Gadite and Reubenite population, not just the negotiating leaders. Josh 22 records the fulfillment: after the conquest, Joshua releases the Transjordan tribes to their inheritance.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The final statement of commitment: 'We will cross over armed before YHWH into Canaan, and our inherited possession will remain with us on this side of the Jordan.' The verse formally encapsulates the deal: the commitment (cross armed into Canaan) paired with the right retained (possession east of the Jordan). The written form of the agreement in v28-32 creates a legal record that functions as the covenant document for the Transjordan inheritance.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Moses assigns the Transjordan to Gad, Reuben, and the half-tribe of Manasseh. The inclusion of Manasseh here is the first mention of their Transjordan inheritance — Num 32 has focused on Gad and Reuben, but by the end of the chapter the Manassites have also acted to take Transjordan territory (v39-42). YHWH's grant includes 'the kingdom of Sihon king of the Amorites and the kingdom of Og king of Bashan' — the two Amorite kingdoms whose defeat in Num 21 opened the Transjordan to Israelite settlement.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The rebuilding inventory begins with Gad: Dibon, Ataroth, and Aroer. The word <em>yivnu</em> (built/rebuilt) implies not new construction but reconstruction of existing cities. The conquering tribes are occupying and restoring pre-existing Amorite settlements, not building from scratch. This is the standard pattern of ancient near eastern conquest: the victor inherits the infrastructure of the conquered.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Additional Gadite rebuilds: Atroth-shophan, Jazer, and Jogbehah. The geographic spread of the cities across the Gilead region reflects the Gadites' claim to a substantial portion of the Transjordan territory. Jazer appears in v1 as one of the cities the petitioners identified as their desired territory — the rebuilding confirms that the original desire became the actual inheritance.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Beth-nimrah ('house of leopards' or 'house of clear water') and Beth-haran — 'all fortified cities' (<em>arey mivtsar</em>) plus sheepfolds (<em>gidroth tzon</em>). The pairing of fortified cities and sheepfolds is the dual requirement the tribes identified in their proposal (v16): they need both defensive strength for their families and functional pastoral infrastructure for their livestock. The final record confirms both needs were met.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Reubenite rebuilds: Heshbon, Elealeh, and Kiriathaim. Heshbon was Sihon's capital (Num 21:26-30) — the Reubenites claim the most prestigious Amorite city as their primary settlement. The choice of Sihon's former capital signals Reuben's claim to the leading position among the Transjordan tribes, consistent with Reuben's firstborn status among Jacob's sons (despite Reuben's historical loss of precedence, Gen 49:3-4).</p>",
    "38": "<p>Nebo and Baal-meon — 'renaming them.' The command to rename cities whose names contain pagan divine names is the Israelite practice of covenant-marking: taking possession of idolatrous places and rededicating them by renaming. Baal-meon (house of Baal) is particularly obvious; Nebo (the Babylonian deity Nabu) is also a pagan name. The Reubenites rename them without preserving the pagan etymologies, though the text notes the original names for historical memory.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The sons of Machir son of Manasseh independently conquer Gilead and drive out the Amorites. The Manassites' military initiative is not explicitly authorized in the preceding negotiations — they take Gilead by conquest rather than by request. This independent military action by Machir echoes the broader pattern: the land is taken by those bold enough to go in and take it, consistent with the caleb-principle of 'following YHWH fully.'</p>",
    "40": "<p>Moses assigns Gilead formally to Machir — the military action (v39) is retrospectively authorized by Moses's official assignment (v40). The sequence (conquest then authorization) is the reverse of the Gad-Reuben pattern (request then conditional grant) but arrives at the same result: YHWH-backed Israelite settlement east of the Jordan. The variety of paths to settlement reflects the providential flexibility of the conquest: YHWH works through both formal negotiation and spontaneous military initiative.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Jair son of Manasseh takes the surrounding villages (<em>chavvotam</em>) and names them Havvoth-jair ('Jair's tent-villages'). The naming of places after their captor/settler is the ancient world's form of title deed — to name is to claim. The cluster of small settlements (<em>chavvot</em>) that Jair names for himself becomes a geographic marker in the Transjordan that endures into the period of the judges (Judg 10:3-4).</p>",
    "42": "<p>Nobah takes Kenath and its surrounding villages (<em>venoteiha</em>) and names the place after himself. The chapter ends with three individual acts of conquest (Machir, Jair, Nobah) — a pattern of personal initiative within the broader tribal assignment. Kenath is the northernmost of the Manassite Transjordan settlements, near the Hauran. The personal naming continues the chapter's theme of individuals claiming and naming their inheritance through personal courage.</p>"
  },
  "33": {
    "1": "<p><strong>eleh mas'ey beney Yisrael asher yatze'u me'eretz Mitzrayim</strong>: 'These are the stages of the Israelites' journey out of Egypt.' Numbers 33 is the Torah's official travel memoir — a comprehensive catalog of the 42 encampments from Egypt to the plains of Moab. The word <em>mas'ey</em> (stages/journeys, from <em>nasa'</em> = to pull up stakes and march) is the technical term for the tabernacle-moving procedure described in Num 10: YHWH's cloud leads, the priests blow trumpets, and each tribe moves in order. The entire wilderness wandering is a series of cloud-led <em>masa</em>-movements.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>vayichtov Moshe et motse'eihem lemasa'eihem al pi YHWH</strong>: 'By YHWH's command, Moses recorded their departures stage by stage.' The wilderness itinerary is not a private travel journal but a divinely commanded document. Moses writes it 'by YHWH's command' — the itinerary has canonical status, not merely historical value. Every campsite and every movement from Egypt to Moab is YHWH's orchestrated journey, worth recording because it is the story of divine faithfulness through forty years of wilderness provision and discipline.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The departure from Rameses: 'the first month, on the fifteenth day — the day after the Passover.' The precise dating (15th of Nisan) places the Exodus in the liturgical calendar — the Passover on the 14th (Lev 23:5), the departure on the 15th. The timing is not incidental: Israel's departure from Egypt is framed as the immediate follow-through of the Passover sacrifice. The Passover lamb's blood opened the exit; the morning after, Israel marched out. 'With a high hand' (<em>beyad ramah</em>) is the idiom for public, triumphant, unhurried departure — the opposite of a secret escape.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>umitzrayim meqabberim et asher hikah YHWH bahem kol bechor</strong>: 'while the Egyptians were burying their firstborn.' The juxtaposition is deliberate: while Egypt buries its firstborn, Israel marches out in triumph. The firstborn judgment (the tenth plague) is what broke Pharaoh's resistance and opened the Exodus. The burial language captures the aftermath — Egypt is occupied with grief while Israel is occupied with liberation. 'The LORD had executed judgments on their gods' — the plagues are simultaneously divine judgments on the specific Egyptian deities associated with the Nile, the sky, the sun, fertility, and death.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Rameses → Succoth: the first stage. Succoth (<em>booths/shelters</em>) may be the Egyptian site of Tell el-Maskhuta, on the eastern edge of the Nile delta. The name anticipates the Feast of Booths (<em>Sukkot</em>), which commemorates the wilderness sojourn (Lev 23:42-43). Israel's first campsite after Egypt is itself named for the temporary shelters that will become the primary metaphor for their wilderness existence — YHWH's people dwell in temporary shelters, pilgrims not settlers, dependent on the cloud for direction and the manna for food.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Succoth → Etham: on 'the edge of the wilderness.' Etham marks the boundary between the settled Nile delta region and the Sinai wilderness — the point of no return. Once Israel crosses from Etham into the wilderness, they have left the predictable provision of Egyptian agriculture for the uncertain provision of YHWH. The wilderness edge is where faith begins.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Etham → Pi-hahiroth: Israel 'turned back' (<em>shav</em>) toward Pi-hahiroth, camping between Migdol and the sea. The doubling-back before the sea is the route that set up the trap: Pharaoh could see that Israel appeared disoriented and trapped (Exod 14:3). Pi-hahiroth's exact location is uncertain; the description (between Migdol and the sea, opposite Baal-zephon) locates it somewhere on the isthmus between the Mediterranean and a body of water crossed in the sea-miracle.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>vayaavru betoch hayam hamidbarah</strong>: 'they passed through the middle of the sea into the wilderness.' The sea-crossing is compressed to a single clause in the itinerary — the most dramatic event of the Exodus is recorded with geographic minimalism: 'through the middle of the sea.' Three days' travel in the wilderness of Etham brings them to Marah, where the waters were bitter until Moses cast a tree into them (Exod 15:23-25). The compressed record makes the sea-crossing a stage in a journey, not a one-time spectacle — YHWH's miraculous acts are the normal means of Israel's travel.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Marah → Elim: 'twelve springs and seventy palms.' Elim is the oasis that follows the bitter-water crisis — the gift of abundance after the trial of thirst. The specific numbers (12 springs = 12 tribes; 70 palms = 70 elders?) may be symbolic or literal; the point is that YHWH follows the test with provision. The oasis of Elim is one of the wilderness narrative's few unambiguously positive sites — no complaints, no crisis, just rest and water.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Elim → Red Sea encampment: Israel camps 'by the Red Sea.' This encampment on the coast of the Gulf of Suez (or Gulf of Aqaba, depending on the route theory) is not mentioned in the main Exodus-Numbers narrative. The itinerary preserves traditions of stations that the narrative did not elaborate. The <em>mas'ot</em> list has independent historical memory, recording movements the main narrative skipped.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Red Sea → wilderness of Sin: the 'Sin' wilderness (not related to the English word 'sin'; the Hebrew is <em>Tzin</em> or <em>Sin</em>) is the Sinai peninsula's central plateau, where Israel first received manna (Exod 16). The wilderness of Sin is the site of the manna-miracle — bread from heaven given to feed a people who had no agricultural land and no stores. This is one of the wilderness's defining provision events, establishing the daily-bread pattern that Jesus will recall in the Lord's Prayer.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Wilderness of Sin → Dophkah: Dophkah is unattested outside this itinerary — possibly the Egyptian turquoise-mining site of Serabit el-Khadim in the Sinai. Many of the intermediate stations between Sin and Sinai are known only from this list. The itinerary preserves names that may reflect local toponymy (Bedouin place-names, Egyptian administrative names, topographic features) rather than Israelite naming.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Dophkah → Alush: another site known only from this list, somewhere in the Sinai peninsula en route to the mountain. The itinerary's value lies partly in its preservation of stations whose stories are not told elsewhere — they represent days of ordinary wilderness travel, marked by YHWH's cloud-guidance but without recorded crisis or miracle.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>ve'en mayim la'am lishto</strong>: 'and there was no water for the people to drink.' Rephidim is the site of the water-from-the-rock miracle (Exod 17:1-7) and the battle with Amalek (Exod 17:8-16). The itinerary notes only the water-crisis, not the miracle or the battle. The parenthetical note preserves the memory of the site's significance: Rephidim is not just a campsite but the place where Israel learned that YHWH provides even in impossible circumstances and that YHWH fights when Israel cannot.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Rephidim → wilderness of Sinai: the arrival at Sinai is the theological center of the entire wilderness journey. The mountain where YHWH appeared, gave the Torah, and established the covenant is the axis around which Numbers' entire narrative orbits. Israel spent approximately a year at Sinai (Exod 19:1 — Num 10:11-12) — the longest stay at any campsite. The itinerary records this as a single stage among others, but the Sinai sojourn encompasses five biblical books' worth of covenant-making.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Sinai → Kibroth-hattaavah ('graves of craving'): the site of the quail-plague judgment (Num 11:4-34). The name is the memorial of divine punishment — people who craved meat instead of trusting YHWH's manna provision were struck down while the meat was still in their mouths. The place-name is a standing sermon: the wilderness landscape is marked by the memory of Israel's failures as well as its triumphs.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Kibroth-hattaavah → Hazeroth: site of Miriam's leprosy-judgment for challenging Moses's authority (Num 12). The movement from the graves-of-craving to Hazeroth carries the narrative weight of two consecutive leadership crises: first the people's craving (Num 11), then Miriam and Aaron's challenge (Num 12). The wilderness journey is not merely geographic but spiritual — the stages map Israel's growing and failing trust in YHWH's provision and leadership.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Hazeroth → Rithmah: unknown site, possibly related to <em>rothem</em> (broom tree). The movement away from Hazeroth begins the long middle section of the itinerary — the 38 years of wilderness wandering between the spy-disaster at Kadesh and the final approach to Moab. Most of the stations in this middle section (v18-36) are unknown and unidentified; they represent the anonymous years of wilderness wandering for the generation condemned to die before the next generation enters the land.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Rithmah → Rimmon-perez: unknown. The name <em>Rimmon-perez</em> (pomegranate of the breach) may preserve memory of a specific incident at the site. The place-names throughout the wilderness journey often encode event-memories — each name is a condensed narrative. Even unknown sites carry names that once had meaning to those who camped there.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Rimmon-perez → Libnah: unknown, possibly 'white tree' or related to the city Libnah in the Shephelah. The itinerary's middle section moves through largely unidentifiable terrain — the wilderness of the Negev and southern Transjordan. The historical memory is preserved in names even when the narrative behind each name is lost.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Libnah → Rissah: unknown. Each stage represents days of march through terrain that provided no permanent landmarks, following a cloud that told them when to go and when to stop. The wilderness itinerary is fundamentally a record of obedience: Israel marched when the cloud lifted and camped when it stayed.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Rissah → Kehelathah: unknown, possibly 'gathering' or 'assembly place' (<em>qahal</em>). The name may preserve a memory of a communal gathering that took place at this site during the forty years. The names are the only windows into the otherwise undocumented middle decades of the wilderness sojourn.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Kehelathah → Mount Shepher: unknown, though <em>shepher</em> may mean 'beauty' or 'hill.' The stations in this section of the itinerary suggest a journey through the highland regions of the Negev and perhaps into the Arabah. The forty years of wandering are not simply idling — the cloud is moving, Israel is moving, and YHWH is managing the timing and direction of the whole pilgrimage.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Mount Shepher → Haradah: possibly 'trembling/fear,' preserving the memory of an event that caused the community to tremble. Place-names in the wilderness frequently encode the emotional register of events — fear, hunger, water-crisis, rebellion, burial — alongside purely geographic description.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Haradah → Makheloth: 'gatherings/assemblies.' Another name in the <em>qahal</em> semantic field, suggesting communal gathering events that marked the site. The assemblies of the wilderness were not always positive — some of the most significant gatherings were rebellion-assemblies (Num 14:1, 16:3). The names preserve both the form (gathering) and let the reader infer the content from the narrative context.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Makheloth → Tahath: 'beneath/below,' possibly a topographic description of a valley or low-lying campsite. The desert terrain of the Negev and Sinai includes dramatic elevation changes — valleys, wadis, and high plateaus. The campsites track the terrain as much as the narrative.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Tahath → Terah: unknown. The shared name with Abraham's father (<em>Terach</em>) may be coincidental topography or may preserve a later folk etymology connecting the patriarch's origin to wilderness geography. The wilderness itinerary covers terrain associated with the patriarchal narratives — Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob traveled through some of the same Negev and Arabah regions.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Terah → Mithkah: 'sweetness.' The name suggests a site with good water or sweet springs — a positive provision memory in the midst of the wilderness wandering. The wilderness is not uniformly harsh; YHWH's provision creates oases of sweetness along the route.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Mithkah → Hashmonah: unknown, possibly related to <em>hashmon</em> (fruitful place). The names cluster around themes of provision, gathering, fear, and geography — the full emotional range of forty years' wandering compressed into place-names.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Hashmonah → Moseroth: unknown, though this may be the same as Moserah where Aaron died (Deut 10:6). If so, the itinerary's sequence differs from Deut 10:6's sequence, a classic textual crux. Moseroth/Moserah is associated with Aaron's death in the Deuteronomy parallel, though Numbers locates Aaron's death at Mount Hor (v38). The variant may preserve different stages of the same journey.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Moseroth → Bene-jaakan: 'sons of Jaakan,' a tribe or clan name associated with wells or cisterns in the Arabah. Deut 10:6 places the Bene-jaakan stage in the context of Aaron's death — the itinerary may preserve an alternate route memory. The wilderness journey involved multiple routes and doubled-back segments; different traditions may have preserved different route sequences.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Bene-jaakan → Hor-haggidgad: 'the cave/pit of Gidgad,' unknown. The name suggests a rocky terrain with caves or hollows — typical of the Negev highlands and Arabah. The specific geography of each campsite would have been vivid to those who lived it and progressively obscure as the narrative passed through generations of transmission.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Hor-haggidgad → Jotbathah: 'a land of rushing brooks' (Deut 10:7). The itinerary's bare name (<em>Yotvatah</em>) is glossed in Deuteronomy as a good-water site — another provision memory encoded in a place-name. The wilderness journey includes genuine oases and life-giving sites alongside the better-known crisis-points.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Jotbathah → Abronah: unknown, possibly 'crossing place' from the root <em>abar</em> (to cross). If so, the name preserves memory of a crossing — a ford, a pass, or a transition point in the journey. The itinerary's names often capture the most memorable feature of each site: water, terrain, event, or crisis.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Abronah → Ezion-geber: identified with Tell el-Kheleifeh at the head of the Gulf of Aqaba. Ezion-geber is the Red Sea port where Solomon later built ships for his Ophir trade (1 Kgs 9:26). Israel's campsite at the head of the Red Sea is a significant southward excursion — the wilderness journey reached the coast before turning north again toward Kadesh. The same Ezion-geber/Elath region will be the starting point of Solomon's maritime empire.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Ezion-geber → wilderness of Zin (Kadesh): the itinerary explicitly identifies this as Kadesh — the central base of operations for the wilderness generation and the site of the spy-disaster. Israel arrives at Kadesh twice in the wilderness narrative: once before the spy episode (Num 13:26) and once at the beginning of the final year (Num 20:1). The itinerary's Kadesh is the second arrival — after thirty-eight years of wandering, the surviving generation returns to the edge of the promised land.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Kadesh → Mount Hor: the penultimate stage before Aaron's death. Mount Hor is on the border of Edom — Israel has completed the Transjordan arc and arrived at the northern frontier of Edom, the traditional territory of Esau's descendants. The location 'on the border of Edom' frames Aaron's death at the edge of the nations who contested Israel's path, a reminder that even the high priest cannot complete the journey he began.</p>",
    "38": "<p><strong>vaya'al Aharon hakohen el Har haHar al pi YHWH vayamot sham bishenat ha'arba'im</strong>: 'Aaron the priest went up Mount Hor at YHWH's command and died there in the fortieth year.' The death of Aaron is the only individual death recorded with a precise date in the itinerary: 'the first day of the fifth month in the fortieth year after the Israelites left Egypt.' The precision marks it as a watershed moment: the last of the original exodus generation's leaders (after Moses and Joshua, who are still living) from the priestly line dies at the edge of the promised land. Aaron never entered what he served toward.</p>",
    "39": "<p><strong>va'Aharon ben esrim ushalosh meah shanah bemoto beHar haHar</strong>: 'Aaron was 123 years old when he died at Mount Hor.' Aaron was born three years before Moses (Exod 7:7 — Aaron was 83 when he stood before Pharaoh), making him the oldest of the wilderness generation's major figures. His 123 years span from Egyptian slavery through the Exodus, covenant-making at Sinai, the golden calf, the institution of the Aaronic priesthood, and forty years of desert ministry. He dies at the edge of the land, as Moses will die at the edge of Moab.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The Canaanite king of Arad hears that Israel is coming — a strategic intelligence note embedded in the itinerary. Arad, in the Negev highlands, had already clashed with Israel (Num 21:1-3) when YHWH gave them victory. The repeated awareness of Israel's approach by Canaanite kings reflects the conquest narrative's military intelligence theme: the nations know YHWH is with Israel (cf. Rahab's testimony in Josh 2:9-11) and respond with fear or resistance.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Mount Hor → Zalmonah: after Aaron's death, the journey resumes immediately. The itinerary does not pause for extended mourning — the cloud moves, and Israel follows. The thirty-day mourning period for Aaron (Num 20:29) occurs within the Mount Hor stage; when it ends, Israel marches on. The wilderness journey's rhythm overrides even the grief of losing the high priest.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Zalmonah → Punon: Punon is tentatively identified with Feinan in modern Jordan, a site with ancient copper mines. The copper mines of Feinan were worked in the Bronze Age and later by Roman prisoners. Israel's campsite at an ancient industrial site is one of the few places where the wilderness journey intersects with known archaeological geography.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Punon → Oboth: unknown, but likely in the Arabah region. The journey is moving northward along the Arabah valley toward the Transjordan, retracing part of the route from Ezion-geber. Oboth is mentioned in Num 21:10 in the context of Israel's movements after the bronze snake incident.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Oboth → Iye-abarim ('ruins of the Abarim'): on Moab's border. The Abarim range is the mountain chain east of the Dead Sea from which Moses will view the promised land and on which he will die (Num 27:12; Deut 32:49). Israel's encampment at Iye-abarim marks their approach to the final stages of the wilderness journey — the Abarim highlands are both the frontier of the promised land and the place of Moses's death.</p>",
    "45": "<p>Iye-abarim → Dibon-gad: on the Arnon plateau, deep in what was Moabite and then Amorite territory. Dibon-gad (Dibon of Gad) anticipates the Gadite settlement of Num 32:34, where Gad rebuilds Dibon as one of its Transjordan cities. The itinerary records Israel's passage through the territory they will eventually inherit.</p>",
    "46": "<p>Dibon-gad → Almon-diblathaim: unknown; the name possibly combines two geographic features ('hidden' + a place). The Arnon plateau region is the area captured from Sihon in Num 21 — Israel's campsite here is in conquered territory, moving through the land YHWH has already given into their hand.</p>",
    "47": "<p>Almon-diblathaim → Abarim mountains before Nebo: Mount Nebo is the peak from which Moses will view the promised land (Deut 34:1) and from which he will die (Deut 34:5). The approach to Nebo is the approach to Moses's death — the itinerary places Israel in the shadow of their leader's end before the narrative records it. Nebo's geographic position (commanding view of all Canaan) makes it the place of both ultimate vision and ultimate unfulfillment: seeing but not entering.</p>",
    "48": "<p>Abarim mountains → plains of Moab by the Jordan. The final encampment is Israel's last wilderness stage — the plains of Moab opposite Jericho, where the Balaam episode took place (Num 22-24) and where Moses will give his final speeches (Deuteronomy). Israel has arrived at the Jordan, the crossing-point into the promised land. The itinerary that began in Egypt ends with Israel one river-crossing away from the fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise.</p>",
    "49": "<p>'Their camp stretched along the Jordan from Beth-jeshimoth to Abel-shittim.' The final encampment occupies a substantial stretch of the Jordan Valley — Israel's wilderness camp has reached its maximum size (the adult males of the second generation, plus families, plus the Levites). Abel-shittim ('meadow of acacias') will be remembered as the site of the Baal-peor apostasy (Num 25:1) and the final sending of the spies before the Jordan crossing (Josh 2:1; 3:1). The plains of Moab are simultaneously the end of the wilderness and the threshold of the promise.</p>",
    "50": "<p>The final divine speech of Numbers (v50-56) is addressed to Moses 'in the plains of Moab by the Jordan at Jericho' — the precise location of the final camp. YHWH gives conquest instructions from the exact threshold of the promised land: when you cross, do this. The instructions anticipate the Joshua narrative (the conquest described in Josh 1-12) and frame it as the continuation of the wilderness journey, not a new chapter but the completion of the journey the itinerary records.</p>",
    "51": "<p><strong>ki ata'avre'u et haYarden el eretz Kena'an</strong>: 'When you cross the Jordan into Canaan.' The conditional 'when' (<em>ki</em>) marks the conquest instructions as the necessary follow-through of the wilderness journey. The Jordan crossing is the event the entire Numbers narrative has been building toward — the generation condemned by the spy-disaster must die; the new generation must cross. The instructions presuppose the crossing's certainty: 'when,' not 'if.'</p>",
    "52": "<p><strong>vehorittem et kol yoshvey ha'aretz milifneichem</strong>: 'Drive out all the land's inhabitants.' The conquest command is total: drive out the inhabitants, destroy the carved stones (<em>maskit</em>), smash the cast images (<em>tzalmey massecah</em>), and demolish all the high places (<em>bamot</em>). The three categories (carved stones, cast images, high places) cover the full spectrum of Canaanite worship infrastructure — the visual media, the metal icons, and the sacred sites. The conquest is as much a religious clearance as a military campaign.</p>",
    "53": "<p><strong>virishtem et ha'aretz vishavtem bah ki lachem natati et ha'aretz lareshet otah</strong>: 'Take possession of the land and live in it, for I have given it to you.' The imperative pair — <em>yoresh</em> (take possession) and <em>yashav</em> (live in) — defines the two dimensions of inheritance: legal possession (title) and actual habitation (occupation). YHWH's gift is the basis of the command: the land is given (<em>natati</em>, perfect tense = already accomplished fact) and Israel must take possession of what YHWH has already given. The gift precedes and grounds the command.</p>",
    "54": "<p><strong>vehitnahaltem et ha'aretz begoral lemishpechotechem</strong>: 'Distribute the land by lot among your clans.' The <em>goral</em> (lot) is YHWH's instrument for the distribution — the allotment is not by military prowess, political negotiation, or personal preference but by divine lot. This prevents both the strong from claiming the best land and the weak from being left with nothing. The lot places the distribution explicitly in YHWH's hands: the lot's outcome is YHWH's decision (Prov 16:33). The larger clans receive larger lots; the smaller, smaller — proportionality within the divine-lot system.</p>",
    "55": "<p><strong>ve'im lo torishu et yoshvey ha'aretz milifneichem vehayah asher totirun mehem lesikim be'eyneichem ulitzinim betzideiichem</strong>: 'But if you do not drive out the land's inhabitants, those you leave will be thorns in your eyes and barbs in your sides.' The warning that closes the wilderness itinerary is the warning that explains the entire book of Judges: Israel failed to drive out the Canaanites; the Canaanites became exactly the thorns and barbs YHWH described. This verse is the prospective explanation of Judges 1-2 — the subsequent history fulfills the warning verbatim.</p>",
    "56": "<p><strong>vehayah ka'asher dimameti la'asot lahem e'eseh lachem</strong>: 'And what I had planned to do to them, I will do to you.' The final verse of the wilderness itinerary — and of Numbers as a whole — is the most severe warning in the book: the judgment prepared for the Canaanites will fall on Israel if they fail to complete the conquest. The symmetry is exact: the same divine action, the same judgment, turned toward the covenant people instead of the covenant people's enemies. This is the logic of covenant curse (Deut 28) applied to conquest failure. Israel does not occupy a privileged position above the law of holy war — they are subject to the same standard they are commanded to apply to Canaan.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'numbers')
    merge_comm(c, NUMBERS)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'numbers', c)
    print('numbers mkt-original: ch 32-33 written')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
